snippet.textDisplay:
Omg! Paulie are you for real? Over the past 6 months all the so-called boxing “experts” were saying that AJ shouldn’t take an immediate rematch because they believed his confidence would be rocked by the initial loss. This guy trusted his instincts, went back to the drawing board, and executed a game plan that ensured that Ruiz and his acclaimed fast hands were largely impotent for the entire 12 rounds.

Considering how the first fight ended, isn’t it common sense that trading with Ruiz is a bad idea. Did you see Ruiz practically begging AJ to stand and trade with him in the final round because he had no answe to AJ’s sleek movement? Over and over again, AJ has proven that he is a beast and he has massive KO power; in this fight he just showed that he can also box. In my opinion, he is becoming an all round fighter and every other to heavyweight should be worried.

Finally, Pauline go to bed! Comparing Ortiz to AJ explains why your boxing record is the way it is. Nonsense!

snippet.textDisplay: This was Joshua’s twenty fourth fight. As a professional heavyweight he’s still learning. To give an example, George Foreman fought for the world title in 1973 against Joe Frazier in his thirty seventh fight. It tells us a few things about AJ, he’s extremely talented, however, he’s also got a huge amount to learn. He doesn’t hold or tie an opponent up. He can’t fight at close range or on the inside. Plus he was reluctant to let his hands go against Ruiz. In the later rounds he should have been hitting Ruiz with hard right hands. He had the power and ability to stop Ruiz, however, inexperience and probably a lack of confidence prevented him from doing so. Hey I’m not putting a downer on AJ. Or being negative. However, it would be great to see AJ moving his head more, developing an overhand right that chops down on the temple and more confidence to let his hands go and then get out of there. Using feints and head movement followed by hard straight punches. AJ is good enough to develop these skills. Personally, I’d keep him away from Wilder and Fury for another year. Give him some easier fights at Wembley. Get his confidence up and develop those skills.
